{"source_key":"sha256-852da461b9759bc2736926d9891eb9a3","record_index":9939,"record_hash":"sha256:2c67f722444685de0b67cb398fe38dce0762598283204ae4e12c096f26ff947f","timestamp":"2026-05-20T18:41:33.381Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: 31d7b9\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 1448\nOutput:\ndraws a useful line:\n\n- tools are model-invoked operations\n- resources are discoverable context\n- prompts are reusable user-controlled workflows\n\nThat maps well to handoff:\n\n- `sessions` and `timeline` are context resources\n- `records` is a read tool\n- a future skill or prompt can teach the catch-up workflow\n\nThe lesson is to make the data browseable and bounded, not to force everything\nthrough one command that returns a wall of text.\n\n### Context Providers And Repo Maps\n\n[Continue context providers](https://docs.continue.dev/customize/custom-providers)\nand [Aider's repository map](https://aider.chat/docs/repomap.html) both show the\nsame pattern: give the model compact orientation first, then let it ask for more\nspecific context. Aider's map is especially relevant because it is not the full\nrepo; it is a token-budgeted outline that guides later reads.\n\nThe lesson is that a handoff command should start with an outline card:\nsessions, turns, counts, agents, recency, branch/review/change hits, and small\npreviews. Full transcript hydration should be a second step.\n\n### Review And Provenance Workflows\n\nDeveloper platforms treat provenance as a lightweight ledger, not just a blob of\nchat. Useful references:\n\n- [GitHub pull request reviews](https://docs.github.[REDACTED:entropy])\n- [GitLab system notes](https://docs.gitlab.com/user/project/system_notes/)\n- [Gerrit Change-Ids](https://gerrit-review.googlesource.com/Documentation/user-changeid.html)\n- [git trailers](https://git-scm.com/docs/git-interpret-trailers.html)\n\nThe lesson is to use stable ids and structured links. Handoff should preserve\nthe relationship between branch, review, change, session, and turn evidence, but\navoid heavyweight supply-chain attestation machinery in v1.\n\n## Research Takeaways\n\nThe handoff feature should copy these ideas:\n\n- branch/work\n[TRUNCATED]\ne metadata: agents, providers, models, tool versions\n- latest turn key and latest capture timestamp\n\nThis command should not hydrate transcript records. It is an index card.\n\n### `timeline`\n\nPurpose: answer \"what happened across this session, and which turns look worth\nreading?\"\n\nExample:\n\n```text\nbut agentlog timeline sha256-9d942495afce65d863ef4d05e61ce2da --limit 20\n```\n\nJSON should include one entry per capture turn:\n\n- `turn_key`\n- `previous_turn_key`\n- `capture_kind`\n- `captured_at`\n- `record_count`\n- environment snapshot status\n- observed branch/review/change target keys\n- first and last record timestamps\n- optional tiny previews of first and latest user text\n\nThis command should not return full transcript records. It should stay cheap\nenough that an agent can run it before deciding what to read.\n\n### `records`\n\nPurpose: answer \"show me the actual transcript records for this turn.\"\n\nExample:\n\n```text\nbut agentlog records sha256-9d942495afce65d863ef4d05e61ce2da \\\n  --turn [REDACTED:entropy] \\\n  --limit 200\n```\n\nJSON should return:\n\n- `session_key`\n- `turn_key`\n- turn metadata\n- ordered transcript records\n- `next_cursor` when more records are available\n\nThe command must be bounded by default. Backfilled turns can contain thousands\nof records, so `records` should never accidentally dump a whole historical\nsession because one turn was large. If the agent needs more, it can follow the\ncursor.\n\n### Optional Later Tool: `search`\n\nSearch is useful, but not needed for the first handoff slice.\n\n```text\nbut agentlog search <query> [branch <branch> | review <review> | change <change>]\n```\n\nAdd this only after the three read tools feel insufficient on real branches.\nThe first version can be plain full-text search over redacted transcript text\nand turn metadata, returning session/turn hits that the agent can inspect with\n`timeline` and `records`.\n\n## Challenge To The Initial Approach\n\nThe core approach is right: let the next agent ask GitButler for relevant\ncontext. The parts I would push on:\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-20T18:41:33.381Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}